Change-Id: Id2a5debe4e7b92a54eaa9f55b678f9fc18459472","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/tensorflow/commits/9a0ea15343d918fa0e8708cfe582578ae8fd032a"},{"sha":"99487be319ca212504742c7b1eeaebaaf71182ae","author":{"name":"Chuanhao Zhuge","email":"2df560f87cba785bae78536bb6567a32ee2f9ce7@google.com"},"message":"Allow configure logical cpu devices after context is initialized.

To configure logical cpu devices, user should either use tf.config.set_logical_device_configuration() before context initialization or use the newly introduced tf.context.context().add_logical_cpu_devices() after context is initialized.

EagerContext's local_device_mgr is changed to use DynamicDeviceMgr to allow adding device after initialization.

Changes in DynamicDeviceMgr:
- Add a constructor that allows taking a list of devices at construction.
- Use vector instead of map to own the devices. This is because there are use cases that require ListDevices() produces the same order as the list of devices being passed in.

[{"sha":"26a2fdcd97033b62854825ac8ace0f681615649c","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Make CreateSummaryFileWriter generate unique filename on every execution

This moves the anti-filename-collision logic from `tf.summary.create_file_writer()` from the Python code wrapping the `CreateSummaryFileWriter` op down into the op kernel itself (specifically, into the `SummaryFileWriter` class in C++). This ensures that we actually get a new filename each time the op executes. Previously this was only true in eager mode - in graph mode, the uniquified `filename_suffix` that the Python code generates would get baked into the graph and reused across executions. Without the suffix uniquification, filenames generated in the same second on the same machine are identical and will clobber each other.

The suffix still consists of the general form `<pid>.<uid>.<user-provided-suffix>`, with two changes:

1. The `uid` is no longer `ops.uid()` but instead a new dedicated counter.
2. In the new logic, if the user-provided suffix doesn't begin with `.` we add one, which avoids some awkwardness in the construction.

Test coverage is added at both the C++ and Python levels.

* fix find zlib.so instead of zlib.a when NDK >= 19

On Android platform, `libopencv_imgcodecs.a` is built, expected to
depend on `libz.so`. However, since Android NDK r19, NDK's `libz.a`
is found instead of `libz.so`, leading to link error
(not found libz.a) on machines without same NDK version & direcotry.

Since Android NDK-r19, toolchain pieces are installed to
`$NDK/toolchains/llvm/prebuilt/<host-tag>/...`, including `libz.so`.
Also installed to old paths (`<NDK>/platforms` and `<NDK>/sysroot`)
in NDK r19, r20, r21, but since NDK 22, old paths are removed.

- https://github.com/android/ndk/wiki/Changelog-r19
- https://github.com/android/ndk/wiki/Changelog-r22

With this commit, `libz.so` can be correctly found in NDK<19 and NDK>=19.

`ZLIB_LIBRARIES` is also simplified as `z`, by appending match (regex)
patterns for new toolchain installation directory's libz.so's paths.

Change-Id: I44d3633be9d6fbebea56a488a5d9a3382c07fb4b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/0546868a385cb10028f831437980934299e3d13b"},{"sha":"26a2fdcd97033b62854825ac8ace0f681615649c","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Make CreateSummaryFileWriter generate unique filename on every execution

This moves the anti-filename-collision logic from `tf.summary.create_file_writer()` from the Python code wrapping the `CreateSummaryFileWriter` op down into the op kernel itself (specifically, into the `SummaryFileWriter` class in C++). This ensures that we actually get a new filename each time the op executes. Previously this was only true in eager mode - in graph mode, the uniquified `filename_suffix` that the Python code generates would get baked into the graph and reused across executions. Without the suffix uniquification, filenames generated in the same second on the same machine are identical and will clobber each other.

The suffix still consists of the general form `<pid>.<uid>.<user-provided-suffix>`, with two changes:

1. The `uid` is no longer `ops.uid()` but instead a new dedicated counter.
2. In the new logic, if the user-provided suffix doesn't begin with `.` we add one, which avoids some awkwardness in the construction.

Test coverage is added at both the C++ and Python levels.

Change-Id: Id2a5debe4e7b92a54eaa9f55b678f9fc18459472","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/9a0ea15343d918fa0e8708cfe582578ae8fd032a"},{"sha":"99487be319ca212504742c7b1eeaebaaf71182ae","author":{"name":"Chuanhao Zhuge","email":"2df560f87cba785bae78536bb6567a32ee2f9ce7@google.com"},"message":"Allow configure logical cpu devices after context is initialized.

To configure logical cpu devices, user should either use tf.config.set_logical_device_configuration() before context initialization or use the newly introduced tf.context.context().add_logical_cpu_devices() after context is initialized.

EagerContext's local_device_mgr is changed to use DynamicDeviceMgr to allow adding device after initialization.

Changes in DynamicDeviceMgr:
- Add a constructor that allows taking a list of devices at construction.

Change-Id: I44d3633be9d6fbebea56a488a5d9a3382c07fb4b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/0546868a385cb10028f831437980934299e3d13b"},{"sha":"26a2fdcd97033b62854825ac8ace0f681615649c","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Make CreateSummaryFileWriter generate unique filename on every execution

This moves the anti-filename-collision logic from `tf.summary.create_file_writer()` from the Python code wrapping the `CreateSummaryFileWriter` op down into the op kernel itself (specifically, into the `SummaryFileWriter` class in C++). This ensures that we actually get a new filename each time the op executes. Previously this was only true in eager mode - in graph mode, the uniquified `filename_suffix` that the Python code generates would get baked into the graph and reused across executions. Without the suffix uniquification, filenames generated in the same second on the same machine are identical and will clobber each other.

The suffix still consists of the general form `<pid>.<uid>.<user-provided-suffix>`, with two changes:

1. The `uid` is no longer `ops.uid()` but instead a new dedicated counter.
2. In the new logic, if the user-provided suffix doesn't begin with `.` we add one, which avoids some awkwardness in the construction.

Test coverage is added at both the C++ and Python levels.

This moves the anti-filename-collision logic from `tf.summary.create_file_writer()` from the Python code wrapping the `CreateSummaryFileWriter` op down into the op kernel itself (specifically, into the `SummaryFileWriter` class in C++). This ensures that we actually get a new filename each time the op executes. Previously this was only true in eager mode - in graph mode, the uniquified `filename_suffix` that the Python code generates would get baked into the graph and reused across executions. Without the suffix uniquification, filenames generated in the same second on the same machine are identical and will clobber each other.

The suffix still consists of the general form `<pid>.<uid>.<user-provided-suffix>`, with two changes:

1. The `uid` is no longer `ops.uid()` but instead a new dedicated counter.
2. In the new logic, if the user-provided suffix doesn't begin with `.` we add one, which avoids some awkwardness in the construction.

Test coverage is added at both the C++ and Python levels.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 366547580
Change-Id: I44d3633be9d6fbebea56a488a5d9a3382c07fb4b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Geolem/tensorflow/commits/0546868a385cb10028f831437980934299e3d13b"},{"sha":"26a2fdcd97033b62854825ac8ace0f681615649c","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Make CreateSummaryFileWriter generate unique filename on every execution

This moves the anti-filename-collision logic from `tf.summary.create_file_writer()` from the Python code wrapping the `CreateSummaryFileWriter` op down into the op kernel itself (specifically, into the `SummaryFileWriter` class in C++). This ensures that we actually get a new filename each time the op executes. Previously this was only true in eager mode - in graph mode, the uniquified `filename_suffix` that the Python code generates would get baked into the graph and reused across executions. Without the suffix uniquification, filenames generated in the same second on the same machine are identical and will clobber each other.

The suffix still consists of the general form `<pid>.<uid>.<user-provided-suffix>`, with two changes:

1. The `uid` is no longer `ops.uid()` but instead a new dedicated counter.
2. In the new logic, if the user-provided suffix doesn't begin with `.` we add one, which avoids some awkwardness in the construction.

Test coverage is added at both the C++ and Python levels.

Change-Id: Ic281c72235f5ed019f11b2ac1a1aaafce7f87718","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/606e8afd4ab34b0c733462b670bb5956641143c6"},{"sha":"cb7f144b577a92d655d8f8c0243219c1dab7dab3","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Pull legacy contrib behavior out of ResourceSummaryWriter

This refactors ResourceSummaryWriter to remove the `v2` parameter, which previously controlled whether the behavior reflected `create_summary_writer()`, aka the legacy tf.contrib.summary API, or `create_summary_writer_v2()`, the API exposed in TF 2. Instead, we just split the behavior into two distinct implementations, `_LegacyResourceSummaryWriter` for contrib and `_ResourceSummaryWriter` for TF 2. This makes each implementation simpler to read in advance of further changes to this class hierarchy.

The symbols have been given leading underscores to discourage their direct usage (since users should refer to the `SummaryWriter` interface only), and I've updated `NoopSummaryWriter` to `_NoopSummaryWriter` accordingly.

This refactors ResourceSummaryWriter to remove the `v2` parameter, which previously controlled whether the behavior reflected `create_summary_writer()`, aka the legacy tf.contrib.summary API, or `create_summary_writer_v2()`, the API exposed in TF 2. Instead, we just split the behavior into two distinct implementations, `_LegacyResourceSummaryWriter` for contrib and `_ResourceSummaryWriter` for TF 2. This makes each implementation simpler to read in advance of further changes to this class hierarchy.

The symbols have been given leading underscores to discourage their direct usage (since users should refer to the `SummaryWriter` interface only), and I've updated `NoopSummaryWriter` to `_NoopSummaryWriter` accordingly.

Change-Id: I63def98da658366339315043530da7884cb26607","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PowerOlive/tensorflow/commits/840686d02134a4073896d0733d7c091487282820"},{"sha":"0546868a385cb10028f831437980934299e3d13b","author":{"name":"Robert David","email":"d592da5c941ed598ace9344e2489e09c28335773@google.com"},"message":"Make unfold_batchmatmul configurable at runtime.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 366547580
Change-Id: I44d3633be9d6fbebea56a488a5d9a3382c07fb4b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PowerOlive/tensorflow/commits/0546868a385cb10028f831437980934299e3d13b"},{"sha":"26a2fdcd97033b62854825ac8ace0f681615649c","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Make CreateSummaryFileWriter generate unique filename on every execution

This moves the anti-filename-collision logic from `tf.summary.create_file_writer()` from the Python code wrapping the `CreateSummaryFileWriter` op down into the op kernel itself (specifically, into the `SummaryFileWriter` class in C++). This ensures that we actually get a new filename each time the op executes. Previously this was only true in eager mode - in graph mode, the uniquified `filename_suffix` that the Python code generates would get baked into the graph and reused across executions. Without the suffix uniquification, filenames generated in the same second on the same machine are identical and will clobber each other.

The suffix still consists of the general form `<pid>.<uid>.<user-provided-suffix>`, with two changes:

1. The `uid` is no longer `ops.uid()` but instead a new dedicated counter.
2. In the new logic, if the user-provided suffix doesn't begin with `.` we add one, which avoids some awkwardness in the construction.

Test coverage is added at both the C++ and Python levels.

Change-Id: Id2a5debe4e7b92a54eaa9f55b678f9fc18459472","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/9a0ea15343d918fa0e8708cfe582578ae8fd032a"},{"sha":"99487be319ca212504742c7b1eeaebaaf71182ae","author":{"name":"Chuanhao Zhuge","email":"2df560f87cba785bae78536bb6567a32ee2f9ce7@google.com"},"message":"Allow configure logical cpu devices after context is initialized.

To configure logical cpu devices, user should either use tf.config.set_logical_device_configuration() before context initialization or use the newly introduced tf.context.context().add_logical_cpu_devices() after context is initialized.

EagerContext's local_device_mgr is changed to use DynamicDeviceMgr to allow adding device after initialization.

Changes in DynamicDeviceMgr:
- Add a constructor that allows taking a list of devices at construction.
- Use vector instead of map to own the devices. This is because there are use cases that require ListDevices() produces the same order as the list of devices being passed in.

Change-Id: Id2a5debe4e7b92a54eaa9f55b678f9fc18459472","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/9a0ea15343d918fa0e8708cfe582578ae8fd032a"},{"sha":"99487be319ca212504742c7b1eeaebaaf71182ae","author":{"name":"Chuanhao Zhuge","email":"2df560f87cba785bae78536bb6567a32ee2f9ce7@google.com"},"message":"Allow configure logical cpu devices after context is initialized.

To configure logical cpu devices, user should either use tf.config.set_logical_device_configuration() before context initialization or use the newly introduced tf.context.context().add_logical_cpu_devices() after context is initialized.

EagerContext's local_device_mgr is changed to use DynamicDeviceMgr to allow adding device after initialization.

Changes in DynamicDeviceMgr:
- Add a constructor that allows taking a list of devices at construction.
- Use vector instead of map to own the devices. This is because there are use cases that require ListDevices() produces the same order as the list of devices being passed in.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 366547580
Change-Id: I44d3633be9d6fbebea56a488a5d9a3382c07fb4b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/0546868a385cb10028f831437980934299e3d13b"},{"sha":"26a2fdcd97033b62854825ac8ace0f681615649c","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Make CreateSummaryFileWriter generate unique filename on every execution

This moves the anti-filename-collision logic from `tf.summary.create_file_writer()` from the Python code wrapping the `CreateSummaryFileWriter` op down into the op kernel itself (specifically, into the `SummaryFileWriter` class in C++). This ensures that we actually get a new filename each time the op executes. Previously this was only true in eager mode - in graph mode, the uniquified `filename_suffix` that the Python code generates would get baked into the graph and reused across executions. Without the suffix uniquification, filenames generated in the same second on the same machine are identical and will clobber each other.

The suffix still consists of the general form `<pid>.<uid>.<user-provided-suffix>`, with two changes:

1. The `uid` is no longer `ops.uid()` but instead a new dedicated counter.
2. In the new logic, if the user-provided suffix doesn't begin with `.` we add one, which avoids some awkwardness in the construction.

Test coverage is added at both the C++ and Python levels.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 366547580
Change-Id: I44d3633be9d6fbebea56a488a5d9a3382c07fb4b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/0546868a385cb10028f831437980934299e3d13b"},{"sha":"26a2fdcd97033b62854825ac8ace0f681615649c","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Make CreateSummaryFileWriter generate unique filename on every execution

This moves the anti-filename-collision logic from `tf.summary.create_file_writer()` from the Python code wrapping the `CreateSummaryFileWriter` op down into the op kernel itself (specifically, into the `SummaryFileWriter` class in C++). This ensures that we actually get a new filename each time the op executes. Previously this was only true in eager mode - in graph mode, the uniquified `filename_suffix` that the Python code generates would get baked into the graph and reused across executions. Without the suffix uniquification, filenames generated in the same second on the same machine are identical and will clobber each other.

The suffix still consists of the general form `<pid>.<uid>.<user-provided-suffix>`, with two changes:

1. The `uid` is no longer `ops.uid()` but instead a new dedicated counter.
2. In the new logic, if the user-provided suffix doesn't begin with `.` we add one, which avoids some awkwardness in the construction.

Test coverage is added at both the C++ and Python levels.

The host tree is a cyclical structure. Leaking a single DOM node can
retain a large amount of memory. React-managed DOM nodes also point
back to a fiber tree.

Perf testing suggests that disconnecting these fields has a big memory
impact. That suggests leaks in non-React code but since it's hard to
completely eliminate those, it may still be worth the extra work to
clear these fields.

I'm moving this to level 2 to confirm whether this alone is responsible
for the memory savings, or if there are other fields that are retaining
large amounts of memory.

retain a large amount of memory. React-managed DOM nodes also point
back to a fiber tree.

impact. That suggests leaks in non-React code but since it's hard to
completely eliminate those, it may still be worth the extra work to
clear these fields.

for the memory savings, or if there are other fields that are retaining

To configure logical cpu devices, user should either use tf.config.set_logical_device_configuration() before context initialization or use the newly introduced tf.context.context().add_logical_cpu_devices() after context is initialized.

EagerContext's local_device_mgr is changed to use DynamicDeviceMgr to allow adding device after initialization.

Changes in DynamicDeviceMgr:
- Add a constructor that allows taking a list of devices at construction.
- Use vector instead of map to own the devices. This is because there are use cases that require ListDevices() produces the same order as the list of devices being passed in.

Since the build scripts will from now on be used in a CI/CD pipeline
they need to be strictly correct, not have bugs and not require manual
intervention. Therefore...

Fixes:
- The Windows build scripts did not incorporate Peter's fix, i.e. creating
  the 'config.h' file as a pre-cursor to the actual build.
  This is now fixed. (compare to build scripts for MacOS and Linux)
- The Windows build script did not include headers from '..\build'
  when compiling. They therefore did not work. This is now fixed.
  (this is a consequence of the JNI headers having been removed from
   source control in commit f395acec1238138ab293516b8819de27403b7219;
   the change was correctly implemented at the time in build scripts
   for Linux and MacOS but for some reason never in build scripts for
   Windows)
- The Windows build scripts will now stop on first error. (checks for
  exit code and abends immediately). The Linux and MacOS scripts do not
  need the same logic as such script can simply be executed with
  'bash -x <script>'.
- The content of the 'config.h' file is now echoed to the console
  as part of the build. This file is crucial to understand the fix
  for the bug reported in NETBEANS-1428.
- Since we will be creating 32-bit binaries on 64-bit platforms
  (because we can no longer find 32-bit hosts to build on):
  The Linux 32-bit script did not create a 32-bit binary for the
  'config' application, hence it produced an incorrect 'config.h' file.
- The Windows build scripts could not handle path names with spaces
  in them as is typical in Windows world. Hence the script did not
  work when executed from a GitHub Action workflow. This is now fixed.
  (too lazy to fix the same problem in the MacOS and Linux scripts;
   on those platforms the problem never manifests itself)
- MacOS script: was hardwired to use the installed JDK rather
  than using the JDK_HOME environment variable. This is now fixed.
- MacOS script: added comments and transparency about how the Universal
  Library mechanism works. (the result of the mechanism is that
  binaries for legacy platforms PowerPC and i386 architectures
  still exist in the bundle but do not receive bug fixes .. meaning
  they'll not as an example receive bug fix for NETBEANS-1428)
- The Windows build scripts used Unix line endings. Although Windows
  doesn't mind this when executing such script it has now been corrected.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tusharjoshi/netbeans/commits/504d66f049e21e7ac4d2205f5f5e2b6ed38bc77a"},{"sha":"c3beb1ea9dd884a7c5f3dff5315b1f5b9eadaeda","author":{"name":"Josh Juneau","email":"142cbbac67b14e561ae41e628cc47909fffa1cea@gmail.com"},"message":"Update ignored-overlaps","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tusharjoshi/netbeans/commits/c3beb1ea9dd884a7c5f3dff5315b1f5b9eadaeda"},{"sha":"1a862ab4f9cdb779bde27692b73694787700e45c","author":{"name":"Lars Bruun-Hansen","email":"f1aeec8b11565a668d6bc7a192ae3850d35af570@apache.org"},"message":"Added GitHub Actions workflow for building native library for lib.profiler

To configure logical cpu devices, user should either use tf.config.set_logical_device_configuration() before context initialization or use the newly introduced tf.context.context().add_logical_cpu_devices() after context is initialized.

EagerContext's local_device_mgr is changed to use DynamicDeviceMgr to allow adding device after initialization.

Changes in DynamicDeviceMgr:
- Add a constructor that allows taking a list of devices at construction.
- Use vector instead of map to own the devices. This is because there are use cases that require ListDevices() produces the same order as the list of devices being passed in.

Change-Id: Id2a5debe4e7b92a54eaa9f55b678f9fc18459472","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/9a0ea15343d918fa0e8708cfe582578ae8fd032a"},{"sha":"99487be319ca212504742c7b1eeaebaaf71182ae","author":{"name":"Chuanhao Zhuge","email":"2df560f87cba785bae78536bb6567a32ee2f9ce7@google.com"},"message":"Allow configure logical cpu devices after context is initialized.

To configure logical cpu devices, user should either use tf.config.set_logical_device_configuration() before context initialization or use the newly introduced tf.context.context().add_logical_cpu_devices() after context is initialized.

EagerContext's local_device_mgr is changed to use DynamicDeviceMgr to allow adding device after initialization.

Changes in DynamicDeviceMgr:
- Add a constructor that allows taking a list of devices at construction.
- Use vector instead of map to own the devices. This is because there are use cases that require ListDevices() produces the same order as the list of devices being passed in.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 366547580
Change-Id: I44d3633be9d6fbebea56a488a5d9a3382c07fb4b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/0546868a385cb10028f831437980934299e3d13b"},{"sha":"26a2fdcd97033b62854825ac8ace0f681615649c","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Make CreateSummaryFileWriter generate unique filename on every execution

This moves the anti-filename-collision logic from `tf.summary.create_file_writer()` from the Python code wrapping the `CreateSummaryFileWriter` op down into the op kernel itself (specifically, into the `SummaryFileWriter` class in C++). This ensures that we actually get a new filename each time the op executes. Previously this was only true in eager mode - in graph mode, the uniquified `filename_suffix` that the Python code generates would get baked into the graph and reused across executions. Without the suffix uniquification, filenames generated in the same second on the same machine are identical and will clobber each other.

The suffix still consists of the general form `<pid>.<uid>.<user-provided-suffix>`, with two changes:

1. The `uid` is no longer `ops.uid()` but instead a new dedicated counter.
2. In the new logic, if the user-provided suffix doesn't begin with `.` we add one, which avoids some awkwardness in the construction.

Test coverage is added at both the C++ and Python levels.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 366547580
Change-Id: I44d3633be9d6fbebea56a488a5d9a3382c07fb4b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/0546868a385cb10028f831437980934299e3d13b"},{"sha":"26a2fdcd97033b62854825ac8ace0f681615649c","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Make CreateSummaryFileWriter generate unique filename on every execution

This moves the anti-filename-collision logic from `tf.summary.create_file_writer()` from the Python code wrapping the `CreateSummaryFileWriter` op down into the op kernel itself (specifically, into the `SummaryFileWriter` class in C++). This ensures that we actually get a new filename each time the op executes. Previously this was only true in eager mode - in graph mode, the uniquified `filename_suffix` that the Python code generates would get baked into the graph and reused across executions. Without the suffix uniquification, filenames generated in the same second on the same machine are identical and will clobber each other.

The suffix still consists of the general form `<pid>.<uid>.<user-provided-suffix>`, with two changes:

1. The `uid` is no longer `ops.uid()` but instead a new dedicated counter.
2. In the new logic, if the user-provided suffix doesn't begin with `.` we add one, which avoids some awkwardness in the construction.

Test coverage is added at both the C++ and Python levels.

[{"sha":"9e3c906aca96739cc263fa1bc9671252fe084c9d","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Pass to mark input-output pairs of cluster_func that read/write to same resource as aliases.

Earlier this was done for device variables only as part of tf-tpu-merge-variables-with-execute pass. Aliasing information (which enables HLO input/output buffer memory optimizations) need not be restricted to same constraints as tf-tpu-merge-variables-with-execute pass.

This change decouples this optimization from tf-tpu-merge-variables-with-execute and adds it as a new pass - tf-tpu-mark-input-output-aliases with relaxed constraints. This enables populating HloInputOutputAliasConfig in HloModuleProto even for those input-outputs corresponding to variables that cannot be merged with TPUExecute (for example, host resource variables) leading to input/output buffer optimization on device.

This captures input output pairs of device computation that read/write to the same resource variable. Passing that information to XLA compiler enables device memory optimization.

* Add feature flag: enableStrongMemoryCleanup

Add a feature flag that will test doing a recursive clean of an unmount
node. This will disconnect the fiber graph making leaks less severe.

* Detach sibling pointers in old child list

When a fiber is deleted, it's still part of the previous (alternate)
parent fiber's list of children. Because children are a linked list, an
earlier sibling that's still alive will be connected to the deleted
fiber via its alternate:


  live fiber
  --alternate--> previous live fiber
  --sibling--> deleted fiber

We can't disconnect `alternate` on nodes that haven't been deleted
yet, but we can disconnect the `sibling` and `child` pointers.

Will use this feature flag to test the memory impact.

* Combine into single enum flag

I combined `enableStrongMemoryCleanup` and `enableDetachOldChildList`
into a single enum flag. The flag has three possible values. Each level
is a superset of the previous one and performs more aggressive clean up.

We will use this to compare the memory impact of each level.

* Add Flow type to new host config method

* Re-use existing recursive clean up path

We already have a recursive loop that visits every deleted fiber. We
can re-use that one for clean up instead of adding another one.

The event priority constants exports by the reconciler package are
meant to be used by the reconciler (host config) itself. So it doesn't
make sense to export them from a module that requires them.

To break the cycle, we can move them to a separate module and import
that. This looks like a "deep import" of an internal module, which we
try to avoid, but conceptually these are part of the public interface
of the reconciler module. So, no different than importing from the main
`react-reconciler`.

We do need to be careful about not mixing these types of imports with
implementation details. Those are the ones to really avoid.

An unintended benefit of the reconciler fork infra is that it makes
deep imports harder. Any module that we treat as "public", like this
one, needs to account for the `enableNewReconciler` flag and forward
to the correct implementation.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PrinceRajRoy/react/commits/d0eaf782930b6e6c575f50bf688e667b9f6795b7"},{"sha":"2c9d8efc8e8202929d3c737459050205f2848d79","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@gmail.com"},"message":"Add react-reconciler/constants entry point (#21062)

[{"sha":"9e3c906aca96739cc263fa1bc9671252fe084c9d","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Pass to mark input-output pairs of cluster_func that read/write to same resource as aliases.

Earlier this was done for device variables only as part of tf-tpu-merge-variables-with-execute pass. Aliasing information (which enables HLO input/output buffer memory optimizations) need not be restricted to same constraints as tf-tpu-merge-variables-with-execute pass.

This change decouples this optimization from tf-tpu-merge-variables-with-execute and adds it as a new pass - tf-tpu-mark-input-output-aliases with relaxed constraints. This enables populating HloInputOutputAliasConfig in HloModuleProto even for those input-outputs corresponding to variables that cannot be merged with TPUExecute (for example, host resource variables) leading to input/output buffer optimization on device.

[{"sha":"9e3c906aca96739cc263fa1bc9671252fe084c9d","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Pass to mark input-output pairs of cluster_func that read/write to same resource as aliases.

Earlier this was done for device variables only as part of tf-tpu-merge-variables-with-execute pass. Aliasing information (which enables HLO input/output buffer memory optimizations) need not be restricted to same constraints as tf-tpu-merge-variables-with-execute pass.

This change decouples this optimization from tf-tpu-merge-variables-with-execute and adds it as a new pass - tf-tpu-mark-input-output-aliases with relaxed constraints. This enables populating HloInputOutputAliasConfig in HloModuleProto even for those input-outputs corresponding to variables that cannot be merged with TPUExecute (for example, host resource variables) leading to input/output buffer optimization on device.

Change-Id: I44d3633be9d6fbebea56a488a5d9a3382c07fb4b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/tensorflow/commits/0546868a385cb10028f831437980934299e3d13b"},{"sha":"26a2fdcd97033b62854825ac8ace0f681615649c","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Make CreateSummaryFileWriter generate unique filename on every execution

This moves the anti-filename-collision logic from `tf.summary.create_file_writer()` from the Python code wrapping the `CreateSummaryFileWriter` op down into the op kernel itself (specifically, into the `SummaryFileWriter` class in C++). This ensures that we actually get a new filename each time the op executes. Previously this was only true in eager mode - in graph mode, the uniquified `filename_suffix` that the Python code generates would get baked into the graph and reused across executions. Without the suffix uniquification, filenames generated in the same second on the same machine are identical and will clobber each other.

The suffix still consists of the general form `<pid>.<uid>.<user-provided-suffix>`, with two changes:

1. The `uid` is no longer `ops.uid()` but instead a new dedicated counter.
2. In the new logic, if the user-provided suffix doesn't begin with `.` we add one, which avoids some awkwardness in the construction.

Test coverage is added at both the C++ and Python levels.

For cross-compiling case, we can't generate the mutable schema easily.
It's complicated to run the target-specific flatc executable on the host
side. So, we can't get the mutable interfaces used in UpdateOpVersion().

This commit checks a definition named "TFLITE_VERSION_USE_MUTABLE_SCHEMA"
for using the immutable and mutable schema header.
If we use the immutable interface, use pack/unpack mechanism to update the

If we don't use "--force-empty-vectors" flag[1] for flatc, the buffers
might be a null ptr if we serialize a model with zero buffers size(e.g.
all ops in model doesn't use const weights in model).
This commit relaxs the "buffers" null ptr checking for this situation,
and also updates the "subgraphs" checking for null ptr dereference.

[{"sha":"9e3c906aca96739cc263fa1bc9671252fe084c9d","author":{"name":"Prakalp Srivastava","email":"7da1985d121fd79537822bb42be62798d2d2aa23@google.com"},"message":"Pass to mark input-output pairs of cluster_func that read/write to same resource as aliases.

Earlier this was done for device variables only as part of tf-tpu-merge-variables-with-execute pass. Aliasing information (which enables HLO input/output buffer memory optimizations) need not be restricted to same constraints as tf-tpu-merge-variables-with-execute pass.

This change decouples this optimization from tf-tpu-merge-variables-with-execute and adds it as a new pass - tf-tpu-mark-input-output-aliases with relaxed constraints. This enables populating HloInputOutputAliasConfig in HloModuleProto even for those input-outputs corresponding to variables that cannot be merged with TPUExecute (for example, host resource variables) leading to input/output buffer optimization on device.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 366547580
Change-Id: I44d3633be9d6fbebea56a488a5d9a3382c07fb4b","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/0546868a385cb10028f831437980934299e3d13b"},{"sha":"26a2fdcd97033b62854825ac8ace0f681615649c","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Make CreateSummaryFileWriter generate unique filename on every execution

This moves the anti-filename-collision logic from `tf.summary.create_file_writer()` from the Python code wrapping the `CreateSummaryFileWriter` op down into the op kernel itself (specifically, into the `SummaryFileWriter` class in C++). This ensures that we actually get a new filename each time the op executes. Previously this was only true in eager mode - in graph mode, the uniquified `filename_suffix` that the Python code generates would get baked into the graph and reused across executions. Without the suffix uniquification, filenames generated in the same second on the same machine are identical and will clobber each other.

The suffix still consists of the general form `<pid>.<uid>.<user-provided-suffix>`, with two changes:

1. The `uid` is no longer `ops.uid()` but instead a new dedicated counter.
2. In the new logic, if the user-provided suffix doesn't begin with `.` we add one, which avoids some awkwardness in the construction.

Test coverage is added at both the C++ and Python levels.

To configure logical cpu devices, user should either use tf.config.set_logical_device_configuration() before context initialization or use the newly introduced tf.context.context().add_logical_cpu_devices() after context is initialized.

EagerContext's local_device_mgr is changed to use DynamicDeviceMgr to allow adding device after initialization.

Changes in DynamicDeviceMgr:
- Add a constructor that allows taking a list of devices at construction.
- Use vector instead of map to own the devices. This is because there are use cases that require ListDevices() produces the same order as the list of devices being passed in.
